  <!-- ═══ WHAT THE MODEL DOESN'T CAPTURE ═══ -->
  <h2>What This Model Doesn't Capture</h2>
  <p>No model is complete. Here's what a DCF inherently misses — and how it might bias our estimate.</p>

  <h3>Upside risks (our number could be too low)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>AI Data Demand:</strong> AI models require massive datasets. If enterprise storage demand for training and inferencing explodes, mass capacity HDD sales could significantly outpace 8% growth.</li>
    <li><strong>Margin Expansion:</strong> HAMR (Heat-Assisted Magnetic Recording) technology transitions could lead to structural gross margin improvements not fully captured in historical FCF.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Downside risks (our number could be too high)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Cyclicality:</strong> The memory and storage markets are notoriously boom-and-bust. A prolonged downturn in cloud capex would crush FCF.</li>
    <li><strong>Technological Obsolescence:</strong> If flash memory (SSD) costs fall faster than HDD costs per terabyte, SSDs could cannibalize mass capacity HDD markets, threatening Seagate's core business.</li>
    <li><strong>Debt Burden:</strong> Seagate carries significant debt (${(totalDebt/1000).toFixed(1)}B). In a rising rate environment or severe downturn, servicing this debt could severely restrict free cash flow.</li>
  </ul>

